## Git vs Gitbub

As explained during the course, Git is a version control system, i.e. a tool to manage your source code history. You can use Git via command line and/or via an IDE.

Github is a hosting service for Git repositories.

## Task 0: Creating a github account

- Create an account on github: [https://github.com/](https://github.com/)  
- Go to the following repository:[https://github.com/weissfennek/lglsi25](https://github.com/weissfennek/lglsi25) and explore its content

## Task 1: Importing a Git project

Follow the instructions on the following link to install Git on your computer:  
[https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Getting-Started-Installing-Git](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Getting-Started-Installing-Git)

Use the following steps to clone (get a copy of) the repository on your computer:

1. Open a terminal  
2. Go the folder location where you want to put the cloned repository  
3. Enter the command git clone and the URL of the repository. So in this case the command will be:

git clone https://github.com/weissfennek/lglsi25.git

Now a copy of the repository is in the folder you selected. You can open the repository from your preferred IDE. In PyCharm for example, you can do this by clicking on File\>open and then select the location of the repository

Note: Many IDEs allow you to clone a git project directly without using the command line, but learning to use the command line is highly recommended. 

## Task2: Creating a branch

Before doing any changes in the code, create a new branch of the project. To do this, click on Git\>New Branch :  
![][image1]

   
Give the branch a name that reflects the change to be made, e.g. “bubble\_sort” and make sure the “Checkout branch” option is selected in order to switch to that branch.  
Now all the changes you will do, will be in the new branch only and will not affect other branches. 

## Task 3: Creating tests

The goal of this task is to create python code along with its tests and add it to the repository.  
In the project there are already at two python files:

- factorial.py includes the code to calculate the factorial of a number  
- Test\_factorial.py includes automated tests to test the factorial.py

Your tasks are:

1. Create a python file including some code. The code can be generated by chatGPT, but you need to check that it is correct.  
2. Create a file that contains tests for the code. The tests should cover edge cases.

Follow the instructions in the following documentation to create automated tests using pytest:  
[https://docs.pytest.org/en/7.1.x/getting-started.html](https://docs.pytest.org/en/7.1.x/getting-started.html)

You can also get some help from chatGPT, **but make sure to verify and test the generated code**

Add the test file to the same folder where you have the code file (It is sometimes a good practice to have a separate test folder, but for now we will keep the tests in the same folder as the code). Call you file test\_\*codeName\*.py. For example, if your code file is called bubbleSort.py then call the test file: test\_bubbleSort.py

When creating the file pyCharm will ask you if you want to add it to Git. Click “add”, otherwise you will need to add it later manually.

**Running the Test**

Right click your file and click on run the test should be run and you should see its result in the terminal. If that doesn’t happen try the following steps:  
In pyCharm go to File\>Settings\>Tools\>Python integrated tools and choose pytest for testing  
![][image2]

Go to Run\>Edit configurations then click on “+” and choose pytest  
In target, select “script path” and add the path to your test file in Target  
Now you can run the test as a pytest by right-clicking the file and then clicking on run by using the green triangle in pyCharm

## Task 4: Commit and push

Now you will push your code to the github repository.  
Right click on the file you added then click on Git\>commit File

![][image3]

Add a comment in which you describe the change you made. Finally click on \*Commit and Push”  
 ![][image4]  
After the push, the changes you made are pushed to the remote github repository.

## Task 5: Create a pull request & Merge

**Pull request**  
Go to the github page of the project then click on “pull requests”.  
![][image5]   
Select the commit you did and click on “compare & pull request”  
![][image6]  
Select weissfennek/lglsi25 as the base repository  
![][image7]

Click on create “pull request”

**Merge**  
To do the merge, you need to be a collaborator in the repository 

Ask to be a collaborator:

- Go to Issues  
  ![][image8]  
- Create a new issue using the “New issue” button  
  ![][image9]  
    
- In the issue description ask to be added as a collaborator for the project  
- In Labels add the label collaborator request![][image10]  
    
- In Assignees, assign the issue to weissfennek   
  


After you have been added as a collaborator to the repository, you can merge the pull request.
